        desc: "Japan is one of the safest countries in the world and, at the same time, the birthplace of a powerful, centuries-old, and far-reaching mafia. The life of the yakuza, the Japanese mafia, is deeply intertwined with that of Japan itself — the yakuza looks after citizens forgotten by the state, engages with politics, participates in economic life, and regulates the criminal underworld. For several years, Martina Baradel has made the yakuza the subject of her study and passionate research. Her work, grounded in the testimonies of those who live on the shadow side of Japan's meticulously ordered society, has earned her the trust of police officers and members of the organisation alike, as well as the very few Japanese journalists who cover the yakuza and who have little patience for the dominant narrative surrounding it. It is through a network of trusted contacts that she manages to secure the meeting from which this investigation takes its departure: a meeting with the boss of one of the largest yakuza families, Tanaka Jun'ichiro, a fictional name under which Martina Baradel gathers the voices and lives of very real people. Meeting after meeting, Tanaka will recount to Martina his life of triumphs and downfalls, and in doing so will allow her to reconstruct the history of the yakuza over the past seventy years, which is, at the same time, the history of Japan over the past seventy years.",
